{"id":"1501.01886","submitter":"Pavel Fileviez Perez","authors":"Pavel Fileviez Perez","title":"New Paradigm for Baryon and Lepton Number Violation","comments":"60 pages, to appear in Physics Reports","journal-ref":"Physics Reports 597 (2015) 1-30","doi":"10.1016/j.physrep.2015.09.001","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph hep-ex hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The possible discovery of proton decay, neutron-antineutron oscillation,\nneutrinoless beta decay in low energy experiments, and exotic signals related\nto the violation of the baryon and lepton numbers at collider experiments will\nchange our understanding of the conservation of fundamental symmetries in\nnature. In this review we discuss the rare processes due to the existence of\nbaryon and lepton number violating interactions. The simplest grand unified\ntheories and the neutrino mass generation mechanisms are discussed. The\ntheories where the baryon and lepton numbers are defined as local gauge\nsymmetries spontaneously broken at the low scale are discussed in detail. The\nsimplest supersymmetric gauge theory which predicts the existence of lepton\nnumber violating processes at the low scale is investigated. The main goal of\nthis review is to discuss the main implications of baryon and lepton number\nviolation in physics beyond the Standard Model.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Jan 2015 14:25:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 17 Aug 2015 20:46:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-09-28"}
{"id":"1501.01933","submitter":"Pierre Gosselet","authors":"Guillaume Guguin (LMT), Olivier Allix (LMT), Pierre Gosselet (LMT),\n  St\\'ephane Guinard","title":"Nonintrusive coupling of 3D and 2D laminated composite models based on\n  finite element 3D recovery","comments":null,"journal-ref":"International Journal for Numerical Methods in Engineering,\n  Wiley-Blackwell, 2014, 98 (5), pp.324-343","doi":"10.1002/nme.4630","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In order to simulate the mechanical behavior of large structures assembled\nfrom thin composite panels, we propose a coupling technique which substitutes\nlocal 3D models for the global plate model in the critical zones where plate\nmodeling is inadequate. The transition from 3D to 2D is based on stress and\ndisplacement distributions associated with Saint-Venant problems which are\nprecalculated automatically for a simple 3D cell. The hybrid plate/3D model is\nobtained after convergence of a series of iterations between a global plate\nmodel of the structure and localized 3D models of the critical zones. This\ntechnique is nonintrusive because the global calculations can be carried out\nusing commercial software. Evaluation tests show that convergence is fast and\nthat the resulting hybrid model is very close to a full 3D model.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Jan 2015 12:32:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-01-09"}
